ce:section.ce:para:
Fluorescence intensity comparison of CDs and CDs(cat.) were presented in Fig. 2a–c, the fluorescence intensity of CDs(cat.) was significantly higher than that of CDs, proving that MnSO4 had significant fluorescence enhancement property on CDs. Meanwhile, we tested the absolute QY of the CDs. The QY of o-CDs(cat.) was tested to be 85.4 % while o-CDs 70.2 %, m-CDs(cat.) was tested to be 35.7 % while m-CDs 20.2 %, p-CDs(cat.) was tested to be 73.8 % while p-CDs 60.1 %. It was indicated that the addition of MnSO4 in the reactant just enhanced fluorescence intensity and fluorescence QY without changing the fluorescence emission wavelength. The fluorescence lifetime of o-CDs(cat.) was calculated to be 6.01 ns while o-CDs was 5.23 ns, m-CDs(cat.) was calculated to be 1.71 ns while m-CDs was 1.68 ns, p-CDs(cat.) was calculated to be 9.03 ns while p-CDs was 7.9 ns (Fig. 2d–f). The fluorescence lifetime of CDs(cat.) was significantly higher than that of CDs, Typically, lifetime changes may be associated with the sp2 conjugated structural domains of CDs. The synthesized CDs(cat.) were evaluated for solvent dependence (relatively stable) (
                           Fig. S2
                        ), thermal stability (excellent) (
                           Fig. S3
                        ), and metal ion quenching (Fe2+, Cu2+ quenching) (
                           Fig. S4
                        ). However, these ions would not present in the application scenario, so they couldn‘t affect their fluorescence performance.

From the FTIR spectra (
                           Fig. S7
                        ), the peak position before and after adding MnSO4 showed almost no significant changes, indicating that the surface structure of the CDs did not alter before and after adding MnSO4, one of the possible reasons was that MnSO4 acts as a catalyst, not involved in chemical reactions.

In order to further analyze the mechanism of MnSO4 catalyzing the synthesis of CDs, we have consulted a large number of literature and learned that MnSO4 reacts to generate MnO2 under hydrothermal conditions [48–50], and MnO2 has a catalytic effect on the synthesis of CDs [51]. We have verified the generation of MnO2 in the experiment, which has been confirmed through FT-IR (
                           Fig. S11
                        ) and XRD (
                           Fig. S12
                        ).

If the ACQ (aggregation-caused quenching) effect appeared in the CDs, the further application of CDs may be seriously limited. To avoid the ACQ phenomenon, CDs(cat.) was doped into starch to obtain CDs(cat.)@starch, which could suppress its aggregation. The abundant chains of starch could be able to prevent the graphitizing cores from π-π interactions. Thus, the CDs(cat.)@starch embedded in the starch kept an appropriate distance from each other, which effectively avoided the consequent fluorescence quenching of solid-state CDs(cat.). The CDs(cat.)@strach showed superior thermal stability (
                           Fig. S14
                        ).
